        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Friends</HEADING>
            <FRIENDSASSOCIATES>
                <DIV2>
                    <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SIB" CHRONCOLUMN1="SOCIALCLIMATE1" RELEVANCE1="DECADE1"> <DATE VALUE="1882-11-" CERTAINTY="BY">Probably by autumn 1882</DATE> <CHRONPROSE>AL became a member of a circle of reforming or socialist women who were mostly regulars in the ladies&apos; lunch room at the <ORGNAME REG="British Library" STANDARD="British Library">British Museum</ORGNAME>.</CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 79" DBREF="8347">79</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </CHRONSTRUCT>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>They included <NAME>Olive Schreiner</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="Webb, Beatrice">the future Beatrice Webb</NAME>, <NAME>Dollie Maitland Radford</NAME>, <NAME>Margaret Harkness</NAME>, <NAME>Clementina Black</NAME> (whose sister <NAME STANDARD="Garnett, Constance">Constance</NAME> had been a school friend of AL), and <NAME>Eleanor Marx</NAME>. Through <NAME>Vernon Lee</NAME> she met <NAME STANDARD="Robinson, A. Mary F.">Mary Robinson</NAME>, whom she had once imagined working for as secretary. As her confidence grew, so did her circle of literary friends.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 79, 130, 120, 242, 129" DBREF="8347">79, 130, 120, 242, 129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Through the club she frequented, she met men of letters like <NAME>George Bernard Shaw</NAME>, <NAME>Augustine Birrell</NAME>, and <NAME>Sidney Lee</NAME>. After 1886, as many of her earlier friends married or invested more of themselves in relationships with men, AL turned to members of homosocial literary circles she had met through Lee, like <NAME>Dorothy Blomfield</NAME>, <NAME>Bertha Thomas</NAME>, and <NAME>Helen Zimmern</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 86, 132" DBREF="8347">86, 132</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                        <P>Others among her friends were <NAME STANDARD="Darwin, Ellen Wordsworth">Ellen Wordsworth Crofts</NAME>, who later became the mother of the poet <NAME>Frances Cornford</NAME>, and <NAME>Karl Pearson</NAME>, mathematician, eugenicist, and founder of the <ORGNAME>Men and Women&apos;s Club</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pullen 115, 98" DBREF="76986">115, 98</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </FRIENDSASSOCIATES>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <POLITICS>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>Her friendship with highly politicised women does not mean, however, that she shared their left-wing views.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 130" DBREF="8347">130</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </POLITICS>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <LEISUREANDSOCIETY>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>She confessed also that to live like <NAME>Clementina Black</NAME> and her sister, doing their own housework, did not accord with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">my own Philistine, middle class notions of comfort.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 255" DBREF="8347" QTDIN="QTDINYES">255</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She engaged, however, in socially provocative behaviour like riding on the open top deck of a bus, a conspicuous position normally occupied only by men.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 139" DBREF="8347">139</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In December 1882 she joined an unnamed club for both sexes (too early for <NAME>Karl Pearson</NAME>&apos;s well-known Men and Women&apos;s Club) which met twice a month, either for talk and music or for the presentation of a paper. She had first registered as a guest in May that year, and late in 1883 the club twice met at her house. Later she did indeed join the <ORGNAME>Men and Women&apos;s Club</ORGNAME>, and she was also an early member of the <ORGNAME REG="University Women&apos;s Club" STANDARD="University Women&apos;s Club">University Women&apos;s Club</ORGNAME> (opened in January 1887), where she found a quiet space free from family demands.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 85-6, 137" DBREF="8347">85-6, 137</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pullen 68" DBREF="76986">68</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LEISUREANDSOCIETY>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Health Problems</HEADING>
            <HEALTH ISSUE="MENTAL">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>Throughout AL&apos;s life her letters refer to the depression which lurked constantly at the edges of her consciousness. In autumn 1885, a few months after her elder sister married, she attempted suicide and was sent to recover at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>St Mawgan-in-Pydar</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION>Cornwall</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pullen 110-11, 116" DBREF="76986">110-11, 116</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </HEALTH>
            <HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>She suffered various problems too with her physical health. In 1881 she had neuralgia and in 1884 an ulcerated sore throat. Her most serious trouble was deafness, which was already bothering her before she was twenty-three.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 243, 206, 251n4" DBREF="8347">243, 206, 251n4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </HEALTH>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Florence</HEADING>
            <LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED">
                <DIV2>
                    <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SIB"> <DATERANGE CERTAINTY="C" FROM="1886-01-" TO="1886-03-24" EXACT="BOTH">Late winter and early spring 1886</DATERANGE> <CHRONPROSE>AL, with <NAME>Clementina Black</NAME>, stayed at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Casa Guidi</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>Florence</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, once the home of <NAME STANDARD="Browning, Elizabeth Barrett">Elizabeth</NAME> and <NAME>Robert Browning</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 116-17" DBREF="8347">116-17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </CHRONSTRUCT>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>This visit too had a recuperative purpose. But AL loved Florence. She hoped to return at around the same time the following year, but had to put off her trip.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 258, 265" DBREF="8347">258, 265</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LOCATION>
