            <INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICYES">
                <DIV2>
                    <HEADING>Vernon Lee</HEADING>
                    <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="DECADE" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RESP="SIB"> <DATE VALUE="1886-11-26" CERTAINTY="AFTER">From November 1886</DATE> <CHRONPROSE>AL addressed letters and love-poems to the writer <NAME>Vernon Lee</NAME>, whom she had met that spring in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Florence</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Italy"></GEOG></PLACE>, and for whom she cherished an unrequited love.</CHRONPROSE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 254-5, 119-21" DBREF="8347">254-5, 119-21</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </CHRONSTRUCT>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>In this, says biographer Christine Pullen, AL was switching her emotional dependence from <NAME>Karl Pearson</NAME> (who, she felt, had betrayed their friendship) to Lee,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pullen 98" DBREF="76986">98</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> who was personally charismatic as well as being a writer with a growing reputation. AL addressed her as <SOCALLED>Miss Paget</SOCALLED>.</P>
