        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>A Last Love?</HEADING>
            <INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICPOSSIBLY">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>AL&apos;s biographer <NAME>Linda Hunt Beckman</NAME> believes that AL fell in love once more in her life, and that the most likely person to have been her beloved was her friend <NAME>Dorothy Blomfield</NAME>. Levy sounded depressed during her second stay in Florence (without Blomfield), and she never saw her again after a meeting on <DATE>31 January 1889</DATE>, a fortnight after getting back to London. Beckman suspects that Blomfield ended the relationship, and that for Levy this was the final straw.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 152" DBREF="8347">152</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>A Last Year</HEADING>
            <LEISUREANDSOCIETY>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>AL&apos;s final months of life were crowded and active. She attended concerts, plays, and lectures, visited galleries and museums, gave an ambitious party, and took her nieces and nephews on outings.</P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LEISUREANDSOCIETY>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <FRIENDSASSOCIATES>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>She saw a good deal of <NAME>Olive Schreiner</NAME>, who called her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the most interesting girl she had met in England,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 179" DBREF="8347" QTDIN="QTDINYES">179</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and also took her on two trips outside London at the very end of her life, in a vain effort to cheer her. She met <NAME>Millicent Garrett Fawcett</NAME> and, in July, <NAME STANDARD="Yeats, W. B.">W. B. Yeats</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Beckman 200, 177, 183" DBREF="8347">200, 177, 183</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P>
